00:00:10.059 --> 00:00:10.725 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA GARR: Hi.

00:00:10.725 --> 00:00:13.790 align:middle line:84%
I'm Lisa Garr, host of
"Gaiam Inspirations."

00:00:13.790 --> 00:00:17.700 align:middle line:84%
John Gray is the author
of 25 bestselling books,

00:00:17.700 --> 00:00:19.550 align:middle line:84%
including "Men Are
from Mars, Women

00:00:19.550 --> 00:00:22.030 align:middle line:84%
Are from Venus," the
number-one bestselling

00:00:22.030 --> 00:00:26.210 align:middle line:84%
book of the last decade and the
number one relationship book

00:00:26.210 --> 00:00:29.660 align:middle line:84%
of all time, with over
50 million books sold

00:00:29.660 --> 00:00:31.720 align:middle line:90%
in 50 different languages.

00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:34.400 align:middle line:84%
In all of his years
working with relationships,

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:36.850 align:middle line:84%
the main thing that
John noticed is

00:00:36.850 --> 00:00:40.940 align:middle line:84%
if people are not healthy in
their minds and their body,

00:00:40.940 --> 00:00:43.500 align:middle line:84%
and if they feel sick
and tired and exhausted,

00:00:43.500 --> 00:00:46.560 align:middle line:84%
then their relationships
aren't going to be happy.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:49.500 align:middle line:84%
So he's joining us today to
talk about his new book, called

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:52.370 align:middle line:84%
"Staying Focused
in a Hyper World,"

00:00:52.370 --> 00:00:53.870 align:middle line:90%
which we are definitely in.

00:00:53.870 --> 00:00:56.910 align:middle line:84%
And it's filled with cutting-age
science that supports

00:00:56.910 --> 00:00:59.090 align:middle line:90%
mental and emotional health.

00:00:59.090 --> 00:00:59.960 align:middle line:90%
Welcome.

00:00:59.960 --> 00:01:02.670 align:middle line:84%
So I just said "cutting-age,"
which was just great

00:01:02.670 --> 00:01:04.220 align:middle line:90%
because that's a whole new term.

00:01:04.220 --> 00:01:04.720 align:middle line:90%
>>JOHN GRAY: It's a new term.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:05.440 align:middle line:90%
And you invented it.

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:05.550 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I did.

00:01:05.550 --> 00:01:07.720 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: It's just a new
age-- cutting edge-- cutting

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:08.750 align:middle line:90%
edge of the new age.

00:01:08.750 --> 00:01:09.583 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Cutting-age.

00:01:09.583 --> 00:01:10.178 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: Yeah.

00:01:10.178 --> 00:01:11.980 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because
that's what happens

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:13.449 align:middle line:90%
when you start to get healthy.

00:01:13.449 --> 00:01:14.490 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: That's true, too.

00:01:14.490 --> 00:01:15.690 align:middle line:90%


00:01:15.690 --> 00:01:17.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I think
that toxicity ages

00:01:17.470 --> 00:01:21.440 align:middle line:84%
us so quickly--
toxicity in terms

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:23.320 align:middle line:90%
of chemicals and thoughts.

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:25.990 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about that
in terms of relationships.

00:01:25.990 --> 00:01:28.240 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Well, that's what I
saw in my own relationship

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:29.090 align:middle line:90%
when I turned 50.

00:01:29.090 --> 00:01:31.760 align:middle line:84%
I've been married to
my wife for 30 years.

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:32.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:01:32.370 --> 00:01:33.870 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: And so we're
in our 60s now.

00:01:33.870 --> 00:01:35.672 align:middle line:84%
But when I turned
50, the passion

00:01:35.672 --> 00:01:36.755 align:middle line:90%
was starting to disappear.

00:01:36.755 --> 00:01:39.130 align:middle line:84%
And here I was, teaching
about these ideas-- helping

00:01:39.130 --> 00:01:40.612 align:middle line:90%
my clients with these ideas.

00:01:40.612 --> 00:01:41.820 align:middle line:90%
And I'm going, what happened?

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:44.890 align:middle line:84%
And what happened is I wasn't
taking care of my brain.

00:01:44.890 --> 00:01:46.850 align:middle line:90%
As many of us-- we think we are.

00:01:46.850 --> 00:01:48.040 align:middle line:90%
I mean, I eat well.

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:48.630 align:middle line:90%
I do well.

00:01:48.630 --> 00:01:49.150 align:middle line:90%
I exercise.

00:01:49.150 --> 00:01:49.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, you do.

00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:50.100 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: All that stuff.

00:01:50.100 --> 00:01:50.400 align:middle line:90%
And then suddenly--

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:51.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You've been
talking about it for years.

00:01:51.290 --> 00:01:51.830 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: Right, right.

00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:53.520 align:middle line:84%
So it has been a
part of my life.

00:01:53.520 --> 00:01:55.450 align:middle line:90%
But something was missing.

00:01:55.450 --> 00:01:58.590 align:middle line:84%
And when I found out what was
missing, it was a revelation.

00:01:58.590 --> 00:02:01.720 align:middle line:84%
The last 15 years of my
marriage have been like heaven.

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:03.850 align:middle line:84%
It was heaven before, but
it was hard work heaven.

00:02:03.850 --> 00:02:04.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:02:04.350 --> 00:02:05.170 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: And I learned
a lot of lessons.

00:02:05.170 --> 00:02:06.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It was
intentional heaven.

00:02:06.030 --> 00:02:07.990 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: And I got a
lot of books out of it

00:02:07.990 --> 00:02:10.370 align:middle line:84%
that explained how to
correctly interpret women,

00:02:10.370 --> 00:02:13.050 align:middle line:84%
how to correctly interpret
men so you don't get so upset.

00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:15.940 align:middle line:84%
But it was still an effort
to put forth all of that.

00:02:15.940 --> 00:02:19.200 align:middle line:84%
And when I got my brain
aligned with my body and health

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:23.540 align:middle line:84%
and vibrancy and focus, which
is a focus of my new book, then

00:02:23.540 --> 00:02:25.090 align:middle line:90%
suddenly it became easy.

00:02:25.090 --> 00:02:26.740 align:middle line:84%
And some people
might say, oh John,

00:02:26.740 --> 00:02:27.970 align:middle line:90%
you're just older and wiser.

00:02:27.970 --> 00:02:29.510 align:middle line:90%
Yes, that's true.

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:31.680 align:middle line:90%
But I have more energy now.

00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:32.840 align:middle line:90%
I have more presence.

00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:34.560 align:middle line:90%
My wife notices a difference.

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:37.680 align:middle line:84%
And we saw I made a
few significant changes

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:39.800 align:middle line:84%
to my health, and it made
a world of difference

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:40.807 align:middle line:90%
in my relationship.

00:02:40.807 --> 00:02:42.140 align:middle line:90%
So that's what I talk about now.

00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:44.710 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So do men
tend to get more

00:02:44.710 --> 00:02:47.390 align:middle line:84%
diffused in their awareness
as they get older?

00:02:47.390 --> 00:02:49.050 align:middle line:84%
I think you had
mentioned this to me.

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:51.049 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Well, there is a
different aging for men

00:02:51.049 --> 00:02:52.230 align:middle line:90%
and women, without a doubt.

00:02:52.230 --> 00:02:55.096 align:middle line:84%
And in relationships, you can
see a relationship has an age.

00:02:55.096 --> 00:02:57.050 align:middle line:84%
And it goes through
stages, as well.

00:02:57.050 --> 00:03:00.080 align:middle line:84%
Men start out focused,
passionate, interested.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:01.400 align:middle line:90%
Women are responsive.

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:02.372 align:middle line:90%
He can do no wrong.

00:03:02.372 --> 00:03:03.830 align:middle line:84%
And then we go
through these stages

00:03:03.830 --> 00:03:06.164 align:middle line:84%
where he gradually
loses interest in that.

00:03:06.164 --> 00:03:07.830 align:middle line:84%
There's just not the
natural motivation.

00:03:07.830 --> 00:03:09.770 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't mean he
doesn't love her.

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:12.170 align:middle line:84%
It's just he doesn't
have the focus on her.

00:03:12.170 --> 00:03:14.435 align:middle line:84%
Life pulls new
directions, and I had

00:03:14.435 --> 00:03:16.060 align:middle line:84%
to understand what
was different there.

00:03:16.060 --> 00:03:19.340 align:middle line:84%
Now women, on the
other hand, they

00:03:19.340 --> 00:03:23.240 align:middle line:84%
tend to become overwhelmed
by the needs of everybody.

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:24.950 align:middle line:90%
And they get stressed out.

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:26.970 align:middle line:84%
They're being pulled in
different directions.

00:03:26.970 --> 00:03:29.110 align:middle line:84%
And then they expect
more from him,

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:31.180 align:middle line:84%
like he's supposed to
solve that problem for her.

00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:34.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can we just go back
to the cave for a second?

00:03:34.010 --> 00:03:38.390 align:middle line:84%
In the cave days, men
didn't-- they were programmed,

00:03:38.390 --> 00:03:40.420 align:middle line:84%
and women were
programmed for survival.

00:03:40.420 --> 00:03:43.090 align:middle line:84%
So they wouldn't stick with
the same woman forever.

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:45.752 align:middle line:84%
They would go on to
procreate to the next woman.

00:03:45.752 --> 00:03:47.960 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Well, now, that's
a big debate because we now

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:50.330 align:middle line:84%
have all this evolutionary
psychology and brain science

00:03:50.330 --> 00:03:51.110 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

00:03:51.110 --> 00:03:54.040 align:middle line:84%
And clearly, violence is
a part of men, as well.

00:03:54.040 --> 00:03:54.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:03:54.540 --> 00:03:56.870 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Now, I've
never hurt anybody.

00:03:56.870 --> 00:03:59.100 align:middle line:90%
So I have a violent part of me.

00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:01.052 align:middle line:84%
But I have a front
part of my brain, which

00:04:01.052 --> 00:04:03.135 align:middle line:84%
has developed over thousands
of years of evolution

00:04:03.135 --> 00:04:05.350 align:middle line:84%
that says, take that
violence, turn it

00:04:05.350 --> 00:04:08.930 align:middle line:84%
into constructive passion, and
make a difference in the world.

00:04:08.930 --> 00:04:10.479 align:middle line:90%
Same thing with sex drive.

00:04:10.479 --> 00:04:11.770 align:middle line:90%
We have this sex drive in here.

00:04:11.770 --> 00:04:14.600 align:middle line:84%
In a guy-- I mean, we make
enough sperm to plant babies

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:15.620 align:middle line:90%
all over the place.

00:04:15.620 --> 00:04:16.500 align:middle line:90%
Women make one egg.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:19.111 align:middle line:84%
But men, we're ready to
look to the next to the next

00:04:19.111 --> 00:04:19.610 align:middle line:90%
to the next.

00:04:19.610 --> 00:04:20.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Evolutionary, yeah.

00:04:20.060 --> 00:04:21.959 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: So if I just had
this part of the brain--

00:04:21.959 --> 00:04:24.333 align:middle line:84%
the back part of the brain,
which rules that part of me--

00:04:24.333 --> 00:04:26.900 align:middle line:84%
then I would want to have one
relationship after another.

00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:28.990 align:middle line:84%
Now I still would like to
have that if I was just

00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:30.100 align:middle line:90%
this part of the brain.

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:30.640 align:middle line:90%
But I'm not.

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:31.870 align:middle line:90%
I'm a whole person.

00:04:31.870 --> 00:04:33.690 align:middle line:84%
I have an emotional
part of my brain,

00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:35.510 align:middle line:84%
which is wanting
intimacy and love

00:04:35.510 --> 00:04:36.757 align:middle line:90%
and wanting to grow in love.

00:04:36.757 --> 00:04:38.840 align:middle line:84%
And I have a front part
of my brain that says, OK,

00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:40.910 align:middle line:84%
what's the best
strategy to do that

00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:42.812 align:middle line:84%
and to direct that
passion in a way that

00:04:42.812 --> 00:04:44.300 align:middle line:90%
can sustain the passion?

00:04:44.300 --> 00:04:46.090 align:middle line:84%
And that takes
relationship skills.

00:04:46.090 --> 00:04:48.740 align:middle line:84%
Now I've written lots of books
on those relationship skills.

00:04:48.740 --> 00:04:49.240 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:04:49.240 --> 00:04:51.950 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: But even with that
information, what I found

00:04:51.950 --> 00:04:53.750 align:middle line:84%
is that passion
started to disappear

00:04:53.750 --> 00:04:57.410 align:middle line:84%
because I was missing nutrition,
and my body had become toxic.

00:04:57.410 --> 00:05:00.010 align:middle line:84%
And no fault of my own because
I was eating good foods.

00:05:00.010 --> 00:05:02.510 align:middle line:84%
But what people don't realize
today is breathing the air,

00:05:02.510 --> 00:05:05.960 align:middle line:84%
drinking the water, driving in
a car, going in an airplane,

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:08.640 align:middle line:84%
eating out at restaurants-- you
are filling up with toxicity.

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:09.776 align:middle line:90%
And I'm super healthy.

00:05:09.776 --> 00:05:11.400 align:middle line:84%
I can't imagine these
other people that

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:13.320 align:middle line:84%
don't eat organic
foods, and they

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:16.010 align:middle line:84%
can't get meats and
chicken and whatever

00:05:16.010 --> 00:05:17.480 align:middle line:90%
that's free of hormones.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:19.522 align:middle line:84%
They're putting all these
things into their body.

00:05:19.522 --> 00:05:21.771 align:middle line:84%
And then when they get sick,
then they go to a doctor.

00:05:21.771 --> 00:05:23.320 align:middle line:84%
And that doctor
gives us antibiotics,

00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:27.220 align:middle line:84%
which kill the good
bacteria in their gut, which

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:30.360 align:middle line:84%
now leads to dementia and
Alzheimer's and Parkinson's

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:31.820 align:middle line:90%
and ADHD.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:33.540 align:middle line:90%
We see it in our society.

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:36.430 align:middle line:84%
If you go down to South
America to indigenous tribes,

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:38.330 align:middle line:84%
as people get older,
they're revered.

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:38.914 align:middle line:90%
They're smart.

00:05:38.914 --> 00:05:39.871 align:middle line:90%
They have great memory.

00:05:39.871 --> 00:05:40.590 align:middle line:90%
They have wisdom.

00:05:40.590 --> 00:05:41.980 align:middle line:90%
They have presence of mind.

00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:43.290 align:middle line:90%
They don't have Parkinson's.

00:05:43.290 --> 00:05:44.620 align:middle line:90%
They don't have Alzheimer's.

00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:47.820 align:middle line:84%
They don't have dementia in
these traditional societies.

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:48.940 align:middle line:90%
What is different?

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:50.780 align:middle line:84%
What is different is
the food and the air

00:05:50.780 --> 00:05:52.738 align:middle line:84%
and the water that we're
putting in our bodies.

00:05:52.738 --> 00:05:53.420 align:middle line:90%
It's huge.

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:56.350 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, it's all farmed
and planted and harvested.

00:05:56.350 --> 00:05:58.530 align:middle line:84%
And it's not in packages
in supermarkets,

00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:01.980 align:middle line:84%
which was basically how most of
the world lives at this point.

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:03.590 align:middle line:84%
And we've got to
get back to farm.

00:06:03.590 --> 00:06:06.790 align:middle line:84%
But with that said,
there's also air pollution

00:06:06.790 --> 00:06:09.440 align:middle line:84%
and environmental pollution
and thought pollution.

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:12.150 align:middle line:84%
So how do we get
our brains aligned

00:06:12.150 --> 00:06:15.310 align:middle line:84%
so that our relationships
do work again,

00:06:15.310 --> 00:06:16.910 align:middle line:90%
so that we're not falling prey?

00:06:16.910 --> 00:06:19.760 align:middle line:84%
And does it change
every 15 years?

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:21.812 align:middle line:84%
Does the body adapt
to a certain regime?

00:06:21.812 --> 00:06:23.770 align:middle line:84%
Like you, maybe, have
been talking about health

00:06:23.770 --> 00:06:24.750 align:middle line:90%
for so long.

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:27.390 align:middle line:84%
So you had a certain regime
that you were a part of.

00:06:27.390 --> 00:06:29.575 align:middle line:84%
And now you had to
morph it a little bit.

00:06:29.575 --> 00:06:30.335 align:middle line:90%
Did you?

00:06:30.335 --> 00:06:32.574 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Oh, I've been
continuing to morph it.

00:06:32.574 --> 00:06:34.490 align:middle line:84%
As you get older, you
need a little extra help

00:06:34.490 --> 00:06:35.640 align:middle line:90%
to keep everything sharp.

00:06:35.640 --> 00:06:38.210 align:middle line:90%


00:06:38.210 --> 00:06:41.060 align:middle line:84%
For me to explain this, to go
a little bit back in time would

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:43.560 align:middle line:84%
be helpful, which
is when I turned 50,

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:45.370 align:middle line:84%
I was diagnosed
with Parkinson's.

00:06:45.370 --> 00:06:47.600 align:middle line:90%
Now I have no Parkinson's now.

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:49.190 align:middle line:90%
But that was 15 years ago.

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:51.510 align:middle line:84%
And here I was, my head
involuntarily shaking.

00:06:51.510 --> 00:06:53.500 align:middle line:90%
And I go, how did this happen?

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:55.420 align:middle line:90%
So I then traced it back.

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:57.150 align:middle line:84%
I found out how it
happened for me.

00:06:57.150 --> 00:06:59.410 align:middle line:84%
It can happen in different
ways for different people.

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:00.909 align:middle line:84%
And then I found a
natural solution.

00:07:00.909 --> 00:07:03.270 align:middle line:84%
And in one year, my
Parkinson's was gone.

00:07:03.270 --> 00:07:05.430 align:middle line:84%
And I've helped now
hundreds of people.

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:07.210 align:middle line:84%
But the real big
thing about this

00:07:07.210 --> 00:07:09.720 align:middle line:84%
is not only helping
that mental condition.

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:13.200 align:middle line:84%
The same condition that gives
rise to Parkinson's gives

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:17.580 align:middle line:84%
rise to ADHD in one out
of five children today.

00:07:17.580 --> 00:07:20.540 align:middle line:84%
A more severe case of that
one condition in the brain

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:23.230 align:middle line:84%
gives rise to 1
out of 50 children

00:07:23.230 --> 00:07:25.130 align:middle line:84%
being autistic
spectrum disorder.

00:07:25.130 --> 00:07:27.560 align:middle line:84%
And in California,
1 out of 20 boys

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:30.860 align:middle line:84%
now-- last year-- autistic
spectrum disorder.

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:33.042 align:middle line:84%
This is off the chart,
unbelievable, catastrophic.

00:07:33.042 --> 00:07:34.000 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh my God, why?

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.270 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: This is
just 30 years ago,

00:07:36.270 --> 00:07:40.220 align:middle line:84%
we had 1 out of 10,000 children
having autistic spectrum

00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:40.900 align:middle line:90%
disorder.

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:43.230 align:middle line:84%
Certainly, there was
some ADHD here and there,

00:07:43.230 --> 00:07:45.100 align:middle line:90%
but nothing like it is now.

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:49.710 align:middle line:84%
And people ask me, they say,
do you think this ADHD is real?

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:52.620 align:middle line:84%
And I say, well, are you
asking should we be giving

00:07:52.620 --> 00:07:55.061 align:middle line:90%
6-year-olds methamphetamines?

00:07:55.061 --> 00:07:55.560 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:57.340 align:middle line:84%
We should not be
giving children drugs.

00:07:57.340 --> 00:07:58.750 align:middle line:90%
That's not a good thing.

00:07:58.750 --> 00:08:00.040 align:middle line:90%
Then well, is it real?

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:01.490 align:middle line:90%
It's very, very real.

00:08:01.490 --> 00:08:04.360 align:middle line:84%
One out of six children have
learning disorders today.

00:08:04.360 --> 00:08:06.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So is it
caught more these days,

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:08.910 align:middle line:84%
or is it actually a
rise in the situation?

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:09.454 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: Both.

00:08:09.454 --> 00:08:10.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's both, OK.

00:08:10.370 --> 00:08:13.170 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: But it's a much bigger
problem than it's ever been.

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:15.920 align:middle line:84%
When I was growing up, I
had ADHD and didn't know it.

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:18.860 align:middle line:84%
It's my ADHD that
also is associated

00:08:18.860 --> 00:08:20.550 align:middle line:90%
with very successful people.

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:22.240 align:middle line:84%
So just because you
have ADHD doesn't

00:08:22.240 --> 00:08:24.360 align:middle line:84%
mean you're going to
not be successful.

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:27.120 align:middle line:84%
I, fortunately, had
tremendous support.

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:27.620 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:08:27.620 --> 00:08:31.160 align:middle line:84%
So I could've become a drug
addict back in the '60s.

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:32.909 align:middle line:84%
But fortunately, the
Beatles went to India

00:08:32.909 --> 00:08:34.159 align:middle line:90%
and learned meditation.

00:08:34.159 --> 00:08:35.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And you went with them.

00:08:35.030 --> 00:08:37.113 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: So I wanted to
meet the Beatles, actually.

00:08:37.113 --> 00:08:38.909 align:middle line:84%
But I ended up
with the Maharishi.

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:40.929 align:middle line:84%
They left, and I became
his personal assistant

00:08:40.929 --> 00:08:41.870 align:middle line:90%
for nine years.

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:43.360 align:middle line:90%
So I was vegetarian.

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:44.120 align:middle line:90%
I cleansed.

00:08:44.120 --> 00:08:45.010 align:middle line:90%
I fasted.

00:08:45.010 --> 00:08:46.010 align:middle line:90%
I meditated.

00:08:46.010 --> 00:08:47.100 align:middle line:90%
I lived in fresh air.

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:48.740 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that was
a great foundation

00:08:48.740 --> 00:08:51.767 align:middle line:90%
to help me treat my ADHD.

00:08:51.767 --> 00:08:53.100 align:middle line:90%
So I didn't have those symptoms.

00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:53.200 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:55.210 align:middle line:84%
Oh, so you did that with
that type of training

00:08:55.210 --> 00:08:55.949 align:middle line:90%
with meditation.

00:08:55.949 --> 00:08:57.740 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: And it helped,
but it really didn't

00:08:57.740 --> 00:08:59.200 align:middle line:90%
heal the original condition.

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:01.290 align:middle line:84%
Now for me-- we're all
a little different.

00:09:01.290 --> 00:09:03.750 align:middle line:84%
For me, the original
condition was in second grade,

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:05.750 align:middle line:84%
I fell out of a tree and
had a big concussion--

00:09:05.750 --> 00:09:08.140 align:middle line:90%
upside down, two-story tree.

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:10.800 align:middle line:84%
Broke both arms-- bones
sticking out my arms.

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:12.232 align:middle line:84%
And they said, how
did I even live

00:09:12.232 --> 00:09:14.440 align:middle line:84%
because if my head had been
turned the slightest bit,

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:16.260 align:middle line:90%
it would've come off.

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:17.100 align:middle line:90%
It was a miracle.

00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:17.850 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh my god.

00:09:17.850 --> 00:09:20.099 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: But I had a concussion--
a serious concussion.

00:09:20.099 --> 00:09:22.349 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You didn't break
your neck, or just your arms?

00:09:22.349 --> 00:09:23.098 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: It didn't.

00:09:23.098 --> 00:09:23.980 align:middle line:90%
But my life changed.

00:09:23.980 --> 00:09:25.500 align:middle line:84%
Now you don't realize
as a second-grader

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:27.416 align:middle line:84%
how your life has changed
because everything's

00:09:27.416 --> 00:09:28.390 align:middle line:90%
growing and changing.

00:09:28.390 --> 00:09:30.410 align:middle line:90%
So that affected my brain.

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:35.310 align:middle line:84%
And so I had the classic ADD
symptoms, which is distracted.

00:09:35.310 --> 00:09:35.810 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:09:35.810 --> 00:09:38.790 align:middle line:84%
I would go off in my world
of creating this and creating

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:39.290 align:middle line:90%
that.

00:09:39.290 --> 00:09:42.470 align:middle line:84%
Typically, what I find
the same condition

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:46.140 align:middle line:84%
that a concussion creates,
also the same condition if you

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:48.330 align:middle line:90%
have antibiotics in your gut.

00:09:48.330 --> 00:09:53.550 align:middle line:84%
If you don't have
good gut bacteria,

00:09:53.550 --> 00:09:57.490 align:middle line:84%
your liver makes a particular
antioxidant called glutathione.

00:09:57.490 --> 00:10:00.170 align:middle line:84%
And that's a new word that
people all need to know about.

00:10:00.170 --> 00:10:04.030 align:middle line:84%
Glutathione is a protein
that your liver makes.

00:10:04.030 --> 00:10:07.260 align:middle line:84%
And it will prevent what's
called oxidative stress

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:08.017 align:middle line:90%
to the brain.

00:10:08.017 --> 00:10:09.600 align:middle line:84%
Any time you have
injury to the brain,

00:10:09.600 --> 00:10:11.000 align:middle line:90%
it's called oxidative stress.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.700 align:middle line:84%
That's two new terms today--
glutathione and oxidative

00:10:13.700 --> 00:10:14.780 align:middle line:90%
stress.

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:20.000 align:middle line:84%
There's over 150,000 studies on
PubMed saying oxidative stress

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.900 align:middle line:84%
is the source of Parkinson's,
is the source of dementia,

00:10:23.900 --> 00:10:26.410 align:middle line:90%
is the source of Asperger's.

00:10:26.410 --> 00:10:28.930 align:middle line:84%
Every one of these
conditions-- ADHD, anxiety,

00:10:28.930 --> 00:10:32.009 align:middle line:84%
depression-- you can find high
levels of oxidative stress

00:10:32.009 --> 00:10:32.550 align:middle line:90%
in the brain.

00:10:32.550 --> 00:10:34.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It just eats
away at the brain?

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:35.300 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: It's a simple
way of looking at.

00:10:35.300 --> 00:10:37.810 align:middle line:84%
It's injury that stays there,
and it doesn't get healed.

00:10:37.810 --> 00:10:38.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh my goodness.

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:40.850 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Now what causes
injury to the brain

00:10:40.850 --> 00:10:42.150 align:middle line:90%
is what's called free radicals.

00:10:42.150 --> 00:10:43.816 align:middle line:84%
Now we've all heard
about free radicals.

00:10:43.816 --> 00:10:46.680 align:middle line:84%
It's hard to figure these things
out, but we've all heard them.

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:49.840 align:middle line:84%
Simply, a free radical is every
time your body makes energy,

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:51.750 align:middle line:90%
a free radical is produced.

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:53.500 align:middle line:84%
And every time a free
radical is produced,

00:10:53.500 --> 00:10:56.480 align:middle line:84%
your body makes an
antioxidant to neutralize it.

00:10:56.480 --> 00:10:57.735 align:middle line:90%
That's glutathione.

00:10:57.735 --> 00:10:58.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:10:58.580 --> 00:10:59.538 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: But guess what?

00:10:59.538 --> 00:11:01.220 align:middle line:84%
Our modern world in
the last 30 years

00:11:01.220 --> 00:11:03.690 align:middle line:84%
has suppressed
glutathione production.

00:11:03.690 --> 00:11:05.690 align:middle line:84%
So here you are, making
all these free radicals,

00:11:05.690 --> 00:11:08.175 align:middle line:84%
and there's no antioxidants
to neutralize it.

00:11:08.175 --> 00:11:10.430 align:middle line:84%
Now people are
eating antioxidants.

00:11:10.430 --> 00:11:12.060 align:middle line:90%
We got a big emphasis on that.

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:12.950 align:middle line:90%
And that helps.

00:11:12.950 --> 00:11:15.160 align:middle line:84%
But your body makes
maybe 10 times

00:11:15.160 --> 00:11:19.270 align:middle line:84%
or 100 times more antioxidants
if it's making glutathione.

00:11:19.270 --> 00:11:22.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can you take glutathione
or do glutathione lotions?

00:11:22.920 --> 00:11:25.380 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: There's all kinds
of ways to get glutathione.

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:27.660 align:middle line:84%
For example, Dr. Perlmutter's
written a book on this.

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:29.410 align:middle line:84%
And he shows one of
his YouTube videos.

00:11:29.410 --> 00:11:32.660 align:middle line:84%
There's a man with Parkinson's--
much more severe than I had

00:11:32.660 --> 00:11:34.080 align:middle line:90%
because I caught it early.

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:37.040 align:middle line:84%
And he's hobbling, and
he can't hardly talk.

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:39.810 align:middle line:84%
And he gives him a
glutathione IV drip.

00:11:39.810 --> 00:11:42.280 align:middle line:84%
And after the drip, he's
walking and he's talking.

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:43.780 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you see it
right before you.

00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:44.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You're kidding.

00:11:44.090 --> 00:11:44.400 align:middle line:90%
Wow.

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:45.330 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: It says,
glutathione does that.

00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:46.396 align:middle line:84%
But the problem is
he's going to have

00:11:46.396 --> 00:11:48.812 align:middle line:84%
to keep going back and getting
those drips again and again

00:11:48.812 --> 00:11:49.350 align:middle line:90%
and again.

00:11:49.350 --> 00:11:51.530 align:middle line:84%
What we want to do
is heal the liver

00:11:51.530 --> 00:11:53.370 align:middle line:84%
so the liver is making
the glutathione.

00:11:53.370 --> 00:11:54.980 align:middle line:84%
And there are
certain supplements

00:11:54.980 --> 00:11:58.140 align:middle line:84%
that you can take, certain
dietary changes you can make,

00:11:58.140 --> 00:12:00.770 align:middle line:84%
certain behavioral changes
you need to make in order

00:12:00.770 --> 00:12:02.790 align:middle line:84%
for your liver to
make glutathione.

00:12:02.790 --> 00:12:04.160 align:middle line:90%
So that's one aspect of it.

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:05.650 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the good
news about this

00:12:05.650 --> 00:12:08.760 align:middle line:84%
is if you are in a relationship
where the relationship is

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:10.490 align:middle line:84%
turning into a
different direction,

00:12:10.490 --> 00:12:12.520 align:middle line:84%
there's attention
that's being lost,

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:14.220 align:middle line:84%
there's not focus
and that passion

00:12:14.220 --> 00:12:16.560 align:middle line:84%
that you had in the
beginning, it definitely

00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:17.810 align:middle line:90%
could be brain chemicals.

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:19.165 align:middle line:90%
And it most likely is.

00:12:19.165 --> 00:12:19.420 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: Oh, it is.

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:20.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It always is.

00:12:20.210 --> 00:12:21.310 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: It's both
in combination.

00:12:21.310 --> 00:12:21.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's huge.

00:12:21.650 --> 00:12:22.530 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: There's a combination.

00:12:22.530 --> 00:12:24.746 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if you don't have
good communication skills,

00:12:24.746 --> 00:12:26.120 align:middle line:84%
you get in an
argument and fight.

00:12:26.120 --> 00:12:27.080 align:middle line:90%
You can't resolve it.

00:12:27.080 --> 00:12:29.300 align:middle line:84%
Now you have an
elevated cortisol level.

00:12:29.300 --> 00:12:31.970 align:middle line:84%
Elevated cortisol--
stress-- inhibits

00:12:31.970 --> 00:12:33.550 align:middle line:90%
glutathione production.

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:35.690 align:middle line:84%
So once you don't have the
glutathione production,

00:12:35.690 --> 00:12:38.140 align:middle line:84%
then you start having
injury in your brain.

00:12:38.140 --> 00:12:40.410 align:middle line:84%
It's always happening, and
then the body heals it.

00:12:40.410 --> 00:12:42.302 align:middle line:84%
But you can't heal it
if you're stressed,

00:12:42.302 --> 00:12:43.510 align:middle line:90%
that being one of the things.

00:12:43.510 --> 00:12:46.402 align:middle line:84%
You can't heal it if you have
a high-carbohydrate diet.

00:12:46.402 --> 00:12:47.860 align:middle line:84%
So if you're eating
lots of sugar--

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:50.026 align:middle line:84%
if you find you're stressed
and you eat sugar, which

00:12:50.026 --> 00:12:53.410 align:middle line:84%
maybe 95% of our society goes
and eats something packaged,

00:12:53.410 --> 00:12:55.640 align:middle line:84%
something sweet,
something that's

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:58.490 align:middle line:84%
going to raise our blood
sugar-- even two pieces of bread

00:12:58.490 --> 00:13:02.202 align:middle line:84%
is like eating 2
tablespoons of sugar.

00:13:02.202 --> 00:13:02.910 align:middle line:90%
Just think of it.

00:13:02.910 --> 00:13:03.940 align:middle line:84%
You eat two pieces
of bread, you've

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:06.170 align:middle line:84%
just put 2 tablespoons
of sugar in your body.

00:13:06.170 --> 00:13:08.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You mean
the white breads--

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:09.340 align:middle line:90%
with the ingredients this--

00:13:09.340 --> 00:13:09.640 align:middle line:90%
>>GRAY: The whole-wheat bread.

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:10.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That too?

00:13:10.350 --> 00:13:13.040 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Yes, yes--
anything in a package.

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:15.380 align:middle line:84%
If you're making it
yourself with stone-ground,

00:13:15.380 --> 00:13:16.500 align:middle line:90%
it's more fiber in it.

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:18.660 align:middle line:84%
It's going to slowly move
into the bloodstream.

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:20.860 align:middle line:84%
But your basic whole-wheat
bread, white bread--

00:13:20.860 --> 00:13:22.460 align:middle line:90%
doesn't matter.

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:24.100 align:middle line:90%
It's 2 tablespoons of sugar.

00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:26.600 align:middle line:84%
A glass of juice-- if you look
in all of your canned juices,

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:28.740 align:middle line:84%
all of your energy
drinks, it's a minimum

00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:32.450 align:middle line:84%
of 20 to 40 grams
of sugar in that.

00:13:32.450 --> 00:13:33.840 align:middle line:90%
Now what's 20 grams?

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:34.940 align:middle line:90%
5 teaspoons.

00:13:34.940 --> 00:13:35.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Five--

00:13:35.590 --> 00:13:37.280 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: And that's your
lowest sugar count--

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:37.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --teaspoons.

00:13:37.490 --> 00:13:38.370 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: --on any
of these drinks.

00:13:38.370 --> 00:13:40.100 align:middle line:84%
Most of them are
40, and some of them

00:13:40.100 --> 00:13:42.070 align:middle line:90%
will say 30 for two servings.

00:13:42.070 --> 00:13:44.750 align:middle line:84%
But who divides their
drink in two glasses?

00:13:44.750 --> 00:13:45.570 align:middle line:90%
You drink it down.

00:13:45.570 --> 00:13:48.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can having those types
of meals throughout the day,

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:51.400 align:middle line:84%
with bread and maybe
an energy drink

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:53.580 align:middle line:84%
and some fruit, which
someone would think, oh,

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:54.830 align:middle line:90%
I've had a whole-wheat toast.

00:13:54.830 --> 00:13:56.710 align:middle line:84%
And then I had a
glass of orange juice,

00:13:56.710 --> 00:14:01.240 align:middle line:84%
and then I had an apple all
within a five-hour period.

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:04.570 align:middle line:84%
Could eating like that, which
sounds like a healthy diet,

00:14:04.570 --> 00:14:07.010 align:middle line:90%
cause diabetes down the road?

00:14:07.010 --> 00:14:10.980 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Well, the Diabetes
Association would say no.

00:14:10.980 --> 00:14:12.780 align:middle line:84%
Diabetes Association
is still saying

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:15.800 align:middle line:84%
sugar has nothing
to do with diabetes.

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:17.980 align:middle line:84%
And you know what,
they're right.

00:14:17.980 --> 00:14:19.010 align:middle line:90%
It's not sugar.

00:14:19.010 --> 00:14:20.482 align:middle line:90%
It's how much sugar.

00:14:20.482 --> 00:14:21.190 align:middle line:90%
That's all it is.

00:14:21.190 --> 00:14:22.200 align:middle line:90%
It's how much sugar.

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:23.690 align:middle line:90%
You got to calculate it.

00:14:23.690 --> 00:14:26.310 align:middle line:84%
Now let's say you had your
orange juice after a meal.

00:14:26.310 --> 00:14:28.620 align:middle line:84%
Then it's going to have
less of a blood sugar spike.

00:14:28.620 --> 00:14:30.980 align:middle line:84%
It's all about when
your blood sugar spikes.

00:14:30.980 --> 00:14:33.150 align:middle line:84%
And so if you're
just not eating much

00:14:33.150 --> 00:14:34.860 align:middle line:84%
and you just have
orange juice, you're

00:14:34.860 --> 00:14:35.940 align:middle line:90%
spiking your blood sugar.

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:38.740 align:middle line:84%
And for a child, that's OK
because they haven't yet

00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:40.600 align:middle line:84%
developed insulin
resistance, which

00:14:40.600 --> 00:14:42.147 align:middle line:90%
eventually leads to diabetes.

00:14:42.147 --> 00:14:43.480 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Over time, that happens.

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:45.021 align:middle line:84%
>>GRAY: Yeah, over
time that happens.

00:14:45.021 --> 00:14:46.400 align:middle line:90%
It's a gradual time it develops.

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:47.680 align:middle line:84%
But now we're getting
so many children

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:48.710 align:middle line:90%
with insulin resistance.

00:14:48.710 --> 00:14:49.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Well, the habits form.

00:14:49.990 --> 00:14:51.220 align:middle line:90%
And the sugar comes in.

00:14:51.220 --> 00:14:54.350 align:middle line:84%
